==Mortality salience==
{{Main|mortality salience}}
The [[mortality salience]] hypothesis&nbsp;(MS) states that if indeed one's cultural worldview, or one's self-esteem, serves a death-denying function, then threatening these constructs should produce defenses aimed at restoring psychological equanimity (i.e.,&nbsp;returning the individual to a state of feeling invulnerable). In the MS&nbsp;paradigm, these "threats" are simply experiential reminders of one's own death. This can, and has, taken many different forms in a variety of study paradigms (e.g.,&nbsp;asking participants to write about their own death;<ref name=GPS/> conducting the experiment near funeral homes or cemeteries;<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pyszczynski | first1 = T. | last2 = Wicklund | first2 = R. A. | last3 = Floresku | first3 = S. | last4 = Koch | first4 = H. | last5 = Gauch | first5 = G. | last6 = Solomon | first6 = S. | last7 = Greenberg | first7 = J. | year = 1996 | title = Whistling in the dark: Exaggerated consensus estimates in response to incidental reminders of mortality | journal = Psychological Science | volume = 7 | issue = 6| pages = 332–336 | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-9280.1996.tb00384.x | s2cid = 12709488 }}</ref> having participants watch graphic depictions of death,<ref name = "Green 1994">{{cite journal | last1 = Greenberg | first1 = J. | last2 = Pyszczynski | first2 = T. | last3 = Solomon | first3 = S. | last4 = Simon | first4 = L. | last5 = Breus | first5 = M. | year = 1994 | title = Role of consciousness and accessibility of death-related thoughts in mortality salience effects | journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology | volume = 67 | issue = 4| pages = 627–637 | doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.67.4.627 | pmid = 7965609 | s2cid = 37679370 }}</ref> etc.). Like the other TMT hypotheses, the literature supporting the MS hypothesis is vast and diverse. For a [[meta-analysis]] of MS&nbsp;research, see Burke ''et al.'' (2010).<ref name = Burke>{{cite journal | last1 = Burke | first1 = B. L. | last2 = Martens | first2 = A. | last3 = Faucher | first3 = E. H. | year = 2010 | title = Two decades of terror management theory: A meta-analysis of mortality salience research | journal = Personality and Social Psychology Review | volume = 14 | issue = 2| pages = 155–195 | doi=10.1177/1088868309352321 | pmid=20097885| s2cid = 206682555 }}</ref>

==Replicability controversy==
{{further|Replication crisis}}
The replicability and interpretation of priming findings has become controversial.<ref name="Bower2012">B. Bower. (2012). The hot and cold of priming: Psychologists are divided on whether unnoticed cues can influence behavior. ''Science News'', '''181''', [http://www.sciencenews.org/view/feature/id/340408/description/The_Hot_and_Cold_of_Priming The Hot and Cold of Priming] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928160208/http://www.sciencenews.org/view/feature/id/340408/description/The_Hot_and_Cold_of_Priming |date=September 28, 2013 }}</ref> Studies in 2012 failed to replicate findings, including age priming,<ref name="Doyen2012">{{cite journal | vauthors = Doyen S, Klein O, Pichon CL, Cleeremans A | title = Behavioral priming: it's all in the mind, but whose mind? | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | article-number = e29081 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22279526 | pmc = 3261136 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0029081 | bibcode = 2012PLoSO...729081D | doi-access = free }}</ref> with additional reports of failure to replicate this and other findings such as social-distance also reported.<ref name="Pashler2012">{{cite journal | vauthors = Pashler H, Coburn N, Harris CR | title = Priming of social distance? Failure to replicate effects on social and food judgments | journal = PLOS ONE | volume = 7 | issue = 8 | article-number = e42510 | year = 2012 | pmid = 22952597 | pmc = 3430642 | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0042510 | bibcode = 2012PLoSO...742510P | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name="PsychFileDrawer2013">PsychFileDrawer, (2013). [http://psychfiledrawer.org/topics/view.php?t=replicability-of-social-and-goal-priming-findings-3-849 Replicability of Social and goal priming findings].</ref>  However, some replications have been successful.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Giolla |first1=Erik Mac |last2=Karlsson |first2=Simon |last3=Neequaye |first3=David A. |last4=Bergquist |first4=Magnus |date=2024-11-12 |title=Evaluating the Replicability of Social Priming Studies |url=https://open.lnu.se/index.php/metapsychology/article/view/3308 |journal=Meta-Psychology |language=en |volume=8 |doi=10.15626/MP.2022.3308 |issn=2003-2714|doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name=":4" />

