{{Short description|Misidentification during memory recall}}
{{See also|False memory}}
In [[psychology]], the '''misattribution of memory''' or '''source misattribution''' is the misidentification of the origin of a [[memory]] by the person making the [[Recall (memory)|memory recall]]. Misattribution is likely to occur when individuals are unable to monitor and control the influence of their attitudes, toward their judgments, at the time of retrieval.<ref name="Payne">{{cite journal | vauthors = Payne BK, Cheng CM, Govorun O, Stewart BD | title = An inkblot for attitudes: affect misattribution as implicit measurement | journal = Journal of Personality and Social Psychology | volume = 89 | issue = 3 | pages = 277–293 | date = September 2005 | pmid = 16248714 | doi = 10.1037/0022-3514.89.3.277 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.392.4775 }}</ref> Misattribution is divided into three components: [[cryptomnesia]], [[false memories]], and [[source-monitoring error|source confusion]]. It was originally noted as one of [[Daniel Schacter]]'s [[The Seven Sins of Memory|seven sins of memory]].<ref name="Schacter" />

