{{cs1 config|name-list-style=vanc|display-authors=6}}
{{Infobox_gene}}
'''ORMDL sphingolipid biosynthesis regulator 3''' is a [[protein]] that in humans is encoded by the ''ORMDL3'' [[gene]].<ref name="entrez">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: ORMDL sphingolipid biosynthesis regulator 3 | url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene/94103 }}</ref> Variants affecting the expression of this gene are associated with asthma in childhood.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Moffatt MF, Kabesch M, Liang L, Dixon AL, Strachan D, Heath S, Depner M, von Berg A, Bufe A, Rietschel E, Heinzmann A, Simma B, Frischer T, Willis-Owen SA, Wong KC, Illig T, Vogelberg C, Weiland SK, von Mutius E, Abecasis GR, Farrall M, Gut IG, Lathrop GM, Cookson WO | title = Genetic variants regulating ORMDL3 expression contribute to the risk of childhood asthma | journal = Nature | volume = 448 | issue = 7152 | pages = 470–3 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17611496 | doi = 10.1038/nature06014 | bibcode = 2007Natur.448..470M | hdl = 2027.42/62682 | s2cid = 4373589 | url = https://deepblue.lib.umich.edu/bitstream/2027.42/62682/1/nature06014.pdf | hdl-access = free }}</ref> Transgenic [[Mouse|mice]] which overexpress human ORMDL3 have increased levels of [[Immunoglobulin E|IgE]]. This correlated with increased numbers of [[macrophage]]s, [[neutrophil]]s, [[eosinophil]]s, [[CD4+ T cells and antitumor immunity|CD4<sup>+</sup>]] and enhanced [[T helper cell|Th2]] [[cytokine]] levels in the lung tissue.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Miller M, Rosenthal P, Beppu A, Mueller JL, Hoffman HM, Tam AB, Doherty TA, McGeough MD, Pena CA, Suzukawa M, Niwa M, Broide DH | title = ORMDL3 transgenic mice have increased airway remodeling and airway responsiveness characteristic of asthma | journal = Journal of Immunology | volume = 192 | issue = 8 | pages = 3475–87 | date = April 2014 | pmid = 24623133 | pmc = 3981544 | doi = 10.4049/jimmunol.1303047 }}</ref>

{{cs1 config|name-list-style=vanc}}
{{Infobox_gene}}
'''Phosphatase and tensin homolog (mutated in multiple advanced cancers 1), pseudogene 1''', also known as '''PTENP1''', is a human [[pseudogene]]<ref name="entrez">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: PTENP1 phosphatase and tensin homolog (mutated in multiple advanced cancers 1), pseudogene 1| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/gene?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=11191| access-date = }}</ref> which has a partial reactivated function as a [[Competing endogenous RNA (CeRNA)|competing endogenous RNA]] regulating  the tumor suppressor gene [[PTEN (gene)|PTEN]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Poliseno L, Salmena L, Zhang J, Carver B, Haveman WJ, Pandolfi PP | title = A coding-independent function of gene and pseudogene mRNAs regulates tumour biology | journal = Nature | volume = 465 | issue = 7301 | pages = 1033–8 | date = June 2010 | pmid = 20577206 | doi = 10.1038/nature09144 | pmc = 3206313 | bibcode = 2010Natur.465.1033P }}*{{lay source |template = cite web|vauthors = Buehler J|url = https://www.quantamagazine.org/the-complex-truth-about-junk-dna-20210901/   |title = The Complex Truth About ‘Junk DNA’|date = September 1, 2021 |website = Quanta Magazine }}</ref>

