{{Short description|Inability to differentiate between self and others}}
{{distinguish|Egoism|Egotism}}
[[File:Egocentrism1.Musfica.png|alt=An orange stick figure in the center of orange concentric circles, with six black stick figures scattered on the rim|thumb|A diagram of egocentrism]]
'''Egocentrism''' refers to difficulty differentiating between self and other. More specifically, it is difficulty in accurately perceiving and understanding perspectives other than one's own.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Elkind |first=David |date=1967 |title=Egocentrism in Adolescence |journal=Child Development |volume=38 |issue=4 |pages=1025–1034 |doi=10.2307/1127100 |jstor=1127100 |pmid=5583052 |issn=0009-3920}}</ref>
Egocentrism is found across the life span: in [[infancy]],<ref name="Onishi, K. H. 2005">{{cite journal |author=Onishi, K. H. |author2=Baillargeon, R.|year=2005|title=Do 15-month-old infants understand false beliefs?|journal=Science|volume=308|issue=5719|pages=255–258|pmid=15821091|pmc=3357322|doi=10.1126/science.1107621|bibcode=2005Sci...308..255O}}</ref> [[early childhood]],<ref name=":1" /><ref name="Wimmer">{{cite journal |author=Wimmer, H. |author2=Perner, J. |year=1983|title=Beliefs about beliefs: Representation and constraining function of wrong beliefs in young children's understanding of deception|journal=Cognition|volume=13|issue=1|pages=103–128|pmid=6681741|url=http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/polisci/faculty/chwe/austen/wimmerperner.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160208005237/http://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/polisci/faculty/chwe/austen/wimmerperner.pdf|archive-date=February 8, 2016|doi=10.1016/0010-0277(83)90004-5|s2cid=17014009}}</ref> [[adolescence]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Adams, G. R. |author2=Jones, R. M.|year=1982|title=Adolescent egocentrism: Exploration into possible contributions of parent-child relations|journal=Journal of Youth and Adolescence|volume=11|issue=1|pages=25–31|doi=10.1007/BF01537814|pmid=24310645|s2cid=24937196}}</ref> and [[adulthood]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{cite journal |author=Keysar, B. |author2=Barr, D. J. |author3=Balin, J. A. |author4=Brauner, J. S. |year=2000 |title=Taking perspective in conversation: The role of mutual knowledge in comprehension |journal=Psychological Science |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=32–38 |doi=10.1111/1467-9280.00211 |pmid=11228840|s2cid=10659981 }}</ref> 
Although egocentric behaviors are less prominent in adulthood, the existence of some forms of egocentrism in adulthood indicates that overcoming egocentrism may be a lifelong development that never achieves completion.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pronin|first1=Emily|last2=Olivola|first2=Christopher Y.|title=Encyclopedia of Human Development|date=2006|publisher=Sage Reference|location=Thousand Oaks, CA|pages=441–442|url=http://go.galegroup.com/ps/i.do?id=GALE%7CCX3466300229&v=2.1&it=r&p=GVRL&sw=w&asid=511ed2d691ff0fe2e05fddeb93158426|access-date=20 Oct 2014}}</ref> Adults appear to be less egocentric than children because they are faster to co

